WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:01.920
Good afternoon, everybody. We

2
00:00:02.840 --> 00:00:05.729
waited a little bit, thinking we might get more,

3
00:00:06.660 --> 00:00:10.460
but we are very thrilled that you're here, and we promise you a

4
00:00:10.500 --> 00:00:14.060
very good session. So today, we will be talking

5
00:00:14.120 --> 00:00:17.180
about, does adherence to oral cancer therapy matter?

6
00:00:19.620 --> 00:00:21.720
Just a brief overview of adherence.

7
00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:26.500
We define it as an active, collaborative choice to follow

8
00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:30.060
a treatment plan. About $100 to $300

9
00:00:30.100 --> 00:00:30.760
billion

10
00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:35.860
can be due to poor adherence, and these are

11
00:00:35.940 --> 00:00:39.820
avoidable costs. They're estimated to exceed $500 billion.

12
00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:43.780
Ten to 25% of all hospitalizations are due to poor

13
00:00:43.820 --> 00:00:47.760
adherence. About 125,000 preventable

14
00:00:47.860 --> 00:00:51.740
deaths due to non-adherence occur in the United

15
00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:55.160
States each year. And then in terms of chronic

16
00:00:56.620 --> 00:01:00.320
health condition management, about 50% of the patients

17
00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:04.640
with chronic diseases do not take their medications as prescribed.

18
00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:08.240
Now, when we bring it back to oncology,

19
00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:12.360
as of January 2026, we know that there are

20
00:01:12.480 --> 00:01:15.740
145 approved oral chemotherapy drugs.

21
00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:19.000
So people have to self-administer those drugs

22
00:01:19.980 --> 00:01:23.560
in semi-chronic fashion. And oral

23
00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:27.460
drugs, looking into the future, are making up more than

24
00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:30.820
30% of the oncology treatment development pipeline.

25
00:01:31.580 --> 00:01:33.980
So as this portfolio of

26
00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:38.040
self-administered cancer treatments grows,

27
00:01:38.500 --> 00:01:42.200
there needs to be an investment in adherence

28
00:01:42.280 --> 00:01:45.960
research, and that would pay large dividends.

29
00:01:47.640 --> 00:01:51.340
What the goal should be when we're focusing on adherence research,

30
00:01:52.100 --> 00:01:55.840
the goal should be in understanding the prevalence, the patterns, the

31
00:01:55.880 --> 00:01:59.660
predictors of poor adherence, and in then developing effective,

32
00:01:59.860 --> 00:02:03.600
scalable, and disseminable adherence-enhancing interventions.

33
00:02:04.030 --> 00:02:06.400
These can have far-reaching effects on

34
00:02:06.460 --> 00:02:10.081
improvement in relapse-free survival

35
00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:13.900
for a variety of cancers. So without further ado,

36
00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:15.619
I'm going to have

37
00:02:16.620 --> 00:02:20.260
our session speakers present on this topic

38
00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:24.060
with a wide variety of flavor. We have Dr.

39
00:02:24.260 --> 00:02:27.340
Rita Hayes talking about breast cancer adherence

40
00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:31.200
to oral agents in breast cancer,

41
00:02:31.860 --> 00:02:35.560
Dr. Morris talking about colorectal cancer and adherence to drugs,

42
00:02:36.020 --> 00:02:39.840
and then I will talk about childhood acute lymphoblastic

43
00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:42.320
leukemia. So with that,

44
00:02:43.320 --> 00:02:46.920
what we want to do today is to make sure that we finish our presentations

45
00:02:47.020 --> 00:02:50.960
first, and then would like to take all the questions, thus

46
00:02:51.020 --> 00:02:54.540
ensuring that you all stay in the room till the end of the session.

47
00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:55.460
So,

48
00:02:56.660 --> 00:02:57.620
Dr. Rita Hayes.

49
00:03:02.580 --> 00:03:05.500
Thank you so much. I'm Katherine Reeder-Hayes.

50
00:03:05.560 --> 00:03:09.060
I'm a breast oncologist and a health services researcher at the University of North

51
00:03:09.140 --> 00:03:13.060
Carolina Lineberger, and I'm so appreciative to

52
00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:16.800
Dr. Bachia and the meeting organizers for inviting me to talk today

53
00:03:16.880 --> 00:03:19.040
about a long-term interest of our lab,

54
00:03:19.900 --> 00:03:21.700
and that is breast cancer

55
00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:26.320
oral therapy adherence, and particularly as it

56
00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:29.240
pertains to long-term oral endocrine therapy.

57
00:03:31.140 --> 00:03:34.660
So I always like to point out that breast oncologists were really the first

58
00:03:34.820 --> 00:03:37.020
users of targeted therapy in cancer,

59
00:03:37.920 --> 00:03:41.400
from 1896 when Dr. George Bateson

60
00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:45.160
described the phenomenon of regression of locally

61
00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:48.080
advanced breast tumors after oophorectomy in young women.

62
00:03:48.660 --> 00:03:52.520
And this observation eventually led to the isolation

63
00:03:52.880 --> 00:03:55.460
of the estrogen receptor at the University of Chicago in the

64
00:03:55.480 --> 00:03:59.460
1950s on mammalian breast cells, and

65
00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:03.060
then to the original assays, steroid binding assays, and then

66
00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:07.240
later immunohistochemical tests to identify estrogen

67
00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:10.880
receptor expression on breast cancers and

68
00:04:10.920 --> 00:04:14.910
therefore serve as a predictive biomarker of this response to this

69
00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:15.780
targeted therapy.

70
00:04:16.661 --> 00:04:20.529
And today, later generation endocrine therapies still are a

71
00:04:20.579 --> 00:04:24.180
cornerstone of systemic therapy for hormone receptor-positive breast

72
00:04:24.240 --> 00:04:27.920
cancer, which makes up about 78% of cases in the

73
00:04:27.940 --> 00:04:31.060
United States, with rising proportions.

74
00:04:31.540 --> 00:04:35.480
And that means that it is now an indicated therapy for about a quarter

75
00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:39.390
of a million new cases of breast cancer diagnosed each year in the

76
00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:42.659
United States, primarily with curative intent.

77
00:04:42.690 --> 00:04:46.400
And when taken as prescribed, endocrine therapy, even though it's

78
00:04:46.460 --> 00:04:50.400
just a pill, as our patients often say, does substantially

79
00:04:50.440 --> 00:04:54.380
cut the risk of breast cancer recurrence by up to 50% and the risk

80
00:04:54.440 --> 00:04:56.620
of breast cancer death by one-third.

81
00:04:57.180 --> 00:05:01.060
And that is certainly a major contributor to the drop

82
00:05:01.100 --> 00:05:04.840
in breast cancer mortality rates that we have observed in the United States

83
00:05:04.900 --> 00:05:08.620
since the introduction of adjuvant tamoxifen in the early mid-1980s.

84
00:05:11.140 --> 00:05:14.000
And as Dr. Bachia referenced earlier, we've really seen an

85
00:05:14.020 --> 00:05:17.860
escalation in oral cancer therapy drug approvals

86
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.360
generally, but certainly in endocrine therapy in the past two

87
00:05:21.480 --> 00:05:25.280
decades. And with the exception of the injected SERD fulvestrant,

88
00:05:25.800 --> 00:05:29.400
all of our novel endocrine therapy drug approvals in the past 20

89
00:05:29.500 --> 00:05:33.220
years have come in pill form. And as

90
00:05:33.360 --> 00:05:37.340
the pace of these approvals has escalated, we've

91
00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:40.570
also seen an increasing number of agents that are used as part of

92
00:05:40.570 --> 00:05:44.540
doublets and used on more complex schedules versus

93
00:05:44.620 --> 00:05:47.969
just the good old once-a-day of the aromatase inhibitors and

94
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:51.520
tamoxifen. And looming on the horizon, we have the predicted

95
00:05:51.560 --> 00:05:55.300
approval of the oral SERD jiradecirant in the adjuvant

96
00:05:55.420 --> 00:05:59.160
setting. That will be our first oral SERD approved for early-stage breast

97
00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:02.128
cancerI'm assuming the approval proceeds.

98
00:06:02.508 --> 00:06:06.128
And as you can imagine, these novel therapies are many, many

99
00:06:06.208 --> 00:06:09.648
times more costly, particularly when they come in novel

100
00:06:09.688 --> 00:06:12.708
doublets compared to earlier generation therapies.

101
00:06:12.748 --> 00:06:16.638
And extending geo-destined to the early-stage setting will

102
00:06:16.648 --> 00:06:20.488
increase that cost burden further manyfold simply

103
00:06:20.528 --> 00:06:23.268
because of that 250,000 number I showed you earlier.

104
00:06:25.648 --> 00:06:29.188
So endocrine therapy is really a case study for all of the different kinds of

105
00:06:29.248 --> 00:06:33.068
challenges that we see with medication adherence in chronic disease

106
00:06:33.148 --> 00:06:36.868
due to its duration of therapy, usually recommended for no less than five

107
00:06:36.968 --> 00:06:40.688
years, a substantial side effect burden across multiple organ

108
00:06:40.788 --> 00:06:44.428
systems, and patient understandings of both the risks and the

109
00:06:44.468 --> 00:06:47.968
benefits of the drug that often differ from the clinician's

110
00:06:48.048 --> 00:06:51.868
evidence-based understanding. Drug costs and access to the

111
00:06:51.928 --> 00:06:55.788
newer agents, as I mentioned, is a problem, in addition to the problems

112
00:06:55.828 --> 00:06:59.338
that all of us have when we try to do anything over and over again every

113
00:06:59.428 --> 00:07:01.708
day with forgetting doses.

114
00:07:03.228 --> 00:07:07.188
A unique problem that we have in breast cancer is the position of this oral

115
00:07:07.228 --> 00:07:11.188
therapy. It comes at the end of a very long treatment cascade for

116
00:07:11.268 --> 00:07:14.938
most patients that includes surgery, chemotherapy,

117
00:07:15.328 --> 00:07:18.358
possibly radiation, possibly breast reconstruction.

118
00:07:18.358 --> 00:07:22.348
And then at the end, just as they're celebrating being over all this

119
00:07:22.408 --> 00:07:26.288
intensive therapy, they are handed a pill and told that this is also an important

120
00:07:26.328 --> 00:07:29.528
part of their treatment. And psychologically, that's really a very

121
00:07:29.748 --> 00:07:30.348
difficult

122
00:07:31.488 --> 00:07:33.688
starting point for great adherence.

123
00:07:34.248 --> 00:07:38.048
And in addition, we don't have any reliable biomarkers of, for

124
00:07:38.348 --> 00:07:41.848
instance, drug levels in these medications, and so we are relying on

125
00:07:41.928 --> 00:07:45.848
indirect and patient-reported measures of adherence.

126
00:07:47.688 --> 00:07:51.398
So we've known for about 15 years now, thanks to the pioneering work of

127
00:07:51.468 --> 00:07:55.358
Don Hershman and the Kaiser Permanente system in Northern California,

128
00:07:55.428 --> 00:07:59.408
that we have a substantial real-world problem with adherence to

129
00:07:59.468 --> 00:08:03.118
these drugs. And Don found that

130
00:08:03.168 --> 00:08:07.148
among Kaiser patients who are uniformly insured in an

131
00:08:07.208 --> 00:08:10.828
integrated health system, people who we would think might be the most

132
00:08:10.908 --> 00:08:14.868
well-resourced in terms of having high adherence to their

133
00:08:14.908 --> 00:08:17.368
medications, only about 60%

134
00:08:18.328 --> 00:08:22.278
of patients with female breast cancer in this system were continuing to take their

135
00:08:22.328 --> 00:08:26.108
drugs and adherent at a threshold of 80% over their five

136
00:08:26.148 --> 00:08:27.008
years of therapy.

137
00:08:29.688 --> 00:08:33.328
And Dr. Hershman's findings led our group to become interested

138
00:08:33.889 --> 00:08:37.768
in the specific question of whether racial differences in

139
00:08:37.838 --> 00:08:41.448
medication adherence could be an explanatory factor in the very

140
00:08:41.568 --> 00:08:45.388
persistent and very pronounced racial gaps in the survival,

141
00:08:45.508 --> 00:08:49.018
specifically of hormone receptor-positive disease that we've

142
00:08:49.048 --> 00:08:52.908
observed in the United States ever since about 30 years

143
00:08:52.968 --> 00:08:54.668
ago when tamoxifen was introduced.

144
00:08:55.528 --> 00:08:58.988
And so we started with multi-payer claims data as well.

145
00:08:59.008 --> 00:09:02.688
We looked at younger commercially insured women and found that, in fact, there

146
00:09:02.788 --> 00:09:04.348
was a substantial racial gap,

147
00:09:05.168 --> 00:09:08.858
first in the initiation of any kind of endocrine therapy, and that that

148
00:09:08.908 --> 00:09:12.728
gap appeared to be concentrated among women who had been previously

149
00:09:12.788 --> 00:09:15.368
treated with chemotherapy as part of their treatment plan.

150
00:09:16.828 --> 00:09:20.708
And then looking at adherence among those who did initiate, we

151
00:09:20.748 --> 00:09:24.688
again found in younger Black women a gap

152
00:09:25.028 --> 00:09:28.468
in medication adherence, measured by medication possession

153
00:09:28.488 --> 00:09:31.978
ratio for Black women under 65, which was not

154
00:09:32.008 --> 00:09:34.748
present among the Medicare-age

155
00:09:34.808 --> 00:09:38.588
population. And one detail that I've really gone back

156
00:09:38.648 --> 00:09:42.428
to over and over again over time, thinking about interventions, is

157
00:09:42.688 --> 00:09:46.268
that the patterns of non-adherence were also different by

158
00:09:46.328 --> 00:09:50.308
race. Young Black women tended to have more of what I call spotty adherence,

159
00:09:50.728 --> 00:09:53.988
so frequent small gaps in medication supply.

160
00:09:54.488 --> 00:09:57.628
And if you think as a clinician, and you're thinking about the kinds of ways that

161
00:09:57.668 --> 00:10:01.648
you might detect a patient having challenges with adherence, such

162
00:10:01.728 --> 00:10:05.548
as pharmacy refill alerts, those are going to be less likely

163
00:10:06.328 --> 00:10:10.308
to go off for a patient who is having frequent problems with some

164
00:10:10.348 --> 00:10:13.648
missed doses as opposed to one big discontinuation or pause.

165
00:10:16.928 --> 00:10:20.768
We have also used national data from Treatment MarketScan to do some of this work.

166
00:10:21.158 --> 00:10:24.648
And I wanted to insert this graphic here just to

167
00:10:24.768 --> 00:10:28.248
highlight that when we define adherence by a

168
00:10:28.308 --> 00:10:31.868
dichotomous threshold, even if it's a clinically rational

169
00:10:31.908 --> 00:10:35.828
dichotomous threshold, we are often missing some

170
00:10:35.868 --> 00:10:38.288
of the granularity and meaning in the story.

171
00:10:38.318 --> 00:10:42.068
And so using trajectory modeling, we've been able to identify

172
00:10:42.088 --> 00:10:45.808
more different patterns of adherence, including people who are super

173
00:10:45.848 --> 00:10:49.678
adherent, people who have a little bit of a decline over time but mostly stay on

174
00:10:49.768 --> 00:10:53.628
track, and people who have a pretty sharp and sudden decline

175
00:10:53.728 --> 00:10:56.028
shortly after initiating the medication.

176
00:10:56.388 --> 00:11:00.207
But the two groups I wanted to call your attention to here are the

177
00:11:00.308 --> 00:11:04.148
steady declining group in the light blue, and then this group in the

178
00:11:04.208 --> 00:11:08.048
purple that has a similar early decline but then has

179
00:11:08.088 --> 00:11:11.668
what I call a rescue or recovery trajectory.

180
00:11:11.708 --> 00:11:15.328
So as interventionists, I think that should get us

181
00:11:15.368 --> 00:11:18.748
thinking, "Okay, who are this group of people?

182
00:11:18.868 --> 00:11:19.828
What is their story?

183
00:11:20.908 --> 00:11:24.658
What are they experiencing that's different that allows them to have a

184
00:11:24.748 --> 00:11:28.388
recovery trajectory? And could we potentially support more

185
00:11:28.428 --> 00:11:31.608
patients to get on a similar recovery trajectory?"

186
00:11:34.288 --> 00:11:37.978
So to dig more into those kinds of factors, we turn to patient-reported

187
00:11:37.978 --> 00:11:41.778
data and specifically to the Carolina Breast Cancer Study, which we were

188
00:11:41.788 --> 00:11:45.068
fortunate enough to be part of data collection for between

189
00:11:45.208 --> 00:11:48.788
2008 and 2013. We asked

190
00:11:49.188 --> 00:11:53.028
Black and non-Black women in this study, which oversamples Black

191
00:11:53.088 --> 00:11:56.988
women at 50%, about their adherence behaviors,

192
00:11:57.088 --> 00:12:00.858
beliefs, and side effects at about two years

193
00:12:00.928 --> 00:12:03.148
after their initial breast cancer diagnosis.

194
00:12:03.628 --> 00:12:07.288
And we found, in short, that essentially every type of adherence

195
00:12:07.448 --> 00:12:11.108
barrier that has been identified in medication adherence literature was more

196
00:12:11.148 --> 00:12:14.288
commonly reported among Black compared to white

197
00:12:14.408 --> 00:12:18.256
women.um, across a number of different domains.

198
00:12:18.776 --> 00:12:22.396
And the Black women were more likely to tell us that they had a negative or

199
00:12:22.476 --> 00:12:26.256
neutral attitude towards whether the benefits of their therapy

200
00:12:26.696 --> 00:12:29.696
really exceeded the problems.

201
00:12:31.136 --> 00:12:35.026
We asked people medication beliefs around endocrine therapy, and

202
00:12:35.096 --> 00:12:38.366
Black women were also more likely to tell us two very interesting

203
00:12:38.396 --> 00:12:42.056
things. First, they were more likely to perceive that their breast

204
00:12:42.096 --> 00:12:45.916
cancer was at very low risk of recurrence, despite the

205
00:12:45.956 --> 00:12:49.756
fact that stage and other biological data from the study suggests that

206
00:12:49.816 --> 00:12:52.476
our Black participants are actually at higher risk of recurrence.

207
00:12:53.116 --> 00:12:57.006
And they were also more likely to report that they believe their risk would not

208
00:12:57.096 --> 00:13:00.566
change substantially if they were to discontinue the medication.

209
00:13:01.216 --> 00:13:04.946
So you can imagine that a patient with this set of beliefs about both

210
00:13:05.136 --> 00:13:08.496
risk and efficacy of the medication might make a very rational

211
00:13:08.516 --> 00:13:12.245
decision not to persist with a drug, particularly if it was causing

212
00:13:12.276 --> 00:13:14.436
them substantial side effect problems.

213
00:13:15.726 --> 00:13:19.636
And using the FACT-ES instrument, we also were able to demonstrate

214
00:13:19.675 --> 00:13:23.286
that in fact, these side effect problems across almost every

215
00:13:23.396 --> 00:13:27.156
domain of endocrine-associated symptom that we asked about, were

216
00:13:27.216 --> 00:13:29.616
also more common among our Black participants.

217
00:13:33.616 --> 00:13:37.456
So this is an adherence framework being used by our group for the

218
00:13:37.516 --> 00:13:41.496
last few years that summarizes some of the research from our own group and

219
00:13:41.596 --> 00:13:45.396
others, based on the WHO's framework of

220
00:13:45.406 --> 00:13:49.216
adherence domains in HIV, which was really the original

221
00:13:49.536 --> 00:13:52.026
subspecialty field doing work in medication adherence.

222
00:13:52.576 --> 00:13:56.156
And I put this here just to remind us all that this is a complicated problem,

223
00:13:56.756 --> 00:14:00.216
that not every patient has the same story for why they may

224
00:14:00.376 --> 00:14:01.076
be

225
00:14:02.216 --> 00:14:05.176
hitting an adherence target or not hitting an adherence target.

226
00:14:05.696 --> 00:14:09.536
And we can start to imagine interventions that may have to look similarly

227
00:14:09.576 --> 00:14:13.356
multifaceted and complex to achieve a helpful

228
00:14:13.396 --> 00:14:14.636
result for our patients.

229
00:14:17.076 --> 00:14:19.596
But before we buzz on to talking about intervention,

230
00:14:20.436 --> 00:14:23.695
we really need to pause and say, "Okay, not only is this problem

231
00:14:23.876 --> 00:14:27.776
common, not only is it pervasive, but

232
00:14:27.836 --> 00:14:31.656
is it actually important for disease outcomes?" And in breast

233
00:14:31.696 --> 00:14:35.156
cancer, I think we have substantial evidence from a variety of sources that

234
00:14:35.176 --> 00:14:37.276
adherence is impactful in outcomes.

235
00:14:37.696 --> 00:14:41.496
So on the left here, we have the older Swedish Breast Cancer

236
00:14:41.716 --> 00:14:45.596
Cooperative Group's randomized controlled trial of planned

237
00:14:45.606 --> 00:14:49.196
discontinuation of tamoxifen at two years, versus the

238
00:14:49.236 --> 00:14:52.956
duration that is now the standard of care for tamoxifen, five

239
00:14:53.036 --> 00:14:56.576
years, demonstrating that earlier discontinuation is

240
00:14:56.616 --> 00:14:59.136
impactful on disease-free survival.

241
00:14:59.156 --> 00:15:02.976
And on the right, we have more data from Don Hirschman showing a dose

242
00:15:03.016 --> 00:15:06.696
response relationship between lower and lower medication possession

243
00:15:06.736 --> 00:15:10.416
ratios of aromatase inhibitors and tamoxifen, and the

244
00:15:10.496 --> 00:15:14.216
overall survival of early-stage breast cancer patients in the Kaiser system.

245
00:15:15.296 --> 00:15:19.176
So using both real-world and randomized data, I think we

246
00:15:19.236 --> 00:15:23.096
can appreciate that a standard duration and a therapeutic

247
00:15:23.136 --> 00:15:26.936
medication possession ratio of endocrine therapy is

248
00:15:27.496 --> 00:15:30.976
impactful on outcomes. Although we will not be doing, of course, randomized

249
00:15:31.036 --> 00:15:33.476
studies in this setting at this time.

250
00:15:36.676 --> 00:15:40.336
And although these are immature data, I think we also have some intriguing

251
00:15:40.376 --> 00:15:44.036
indicators from the Carolina Breast Cancer Study, where we have looked at the

252
00:15:44.046 --> 00:15:47.956
association of race and non-adherence, where we have seen

253
00:15:48.056 --> 00:15:51.696
among hormone receptor-positive and HER2-negative patients after

254
00:15:51.716 --> 00:15:55.656
controlling for biological factors and their age, that adherent

255
00:15:55.736 --> 00:15:57.456
patients tend to have a

256
00:15:58.316 --> 00:16:01.996
similarly low risk of recurrence across

257
00:16:02.116 --> 00:16:04.216
both Black and white participants.

258
00:16:04.676 --> 00:16:06.776
But that the increased risk

259
00:16:07.736 --> 00:16:10.796
for non-adherent participants seems to be

260
00:16:11.276 --> 00:16:13.816
concentrated among Black participants.

261
00:16:14.156 --> 00:16:17.716
We have a number of different hypotheses that we're investigating about why this

262
00:16:17.776 --> 00:16:21.676
may be, from differences in the underlying biology of the tumor, that

263
00:16:21.696 --> 00:16:25.616
perhaps require more stringent adherence in order to get the benefits of endocrine

264
00:16:25.676 --> 00:16:29.205
therapy, or potential differences in the duration or the

265
00:16:29.396 --> 00:16:33.156
depth of non-adherence among Black women who are not being

266
00:16:33.235 --> 00:16:35.776
supported to get back on a recovery trajectory.

267
00:16:35.805 --> 00:16:39.756
And so a cross-sectional moment of non-adherence turns into

268
00:16:40.116 --> 00:16:42.816
a longitudinal lower effective dose.

269
00:16:47.036 --> 00:16:50.696
So based on these data, I'm happy to say that this field has been

270
00:16:50.736 --> 00:16:54.286
moving in the last five years from observational research to more

271
00:16:54.336 --> 00:16:57.976
interventional research. And here on this slide, I have listed the

272
00:16:58.016 --> 00:17:01.836
completed and ongoing randomized clinical trials of adherence

273
00:17:01.916 --> 00:17:03.756
interventions in the breast cancer space.

274
00:17:04.456 --> 00:17:08.316
SWOG 1105 was the first. This is Don Hirschman's trial,

275
00:17:09.017 --> 00:17:10.416
looking at an unselected

276
00:17:11.356 --> 00:17:14.536
breast cancer survivor population on aromatase inhibitors,

277
00:17:15.296 --> 00:17:19.136
and they were randomized to usual care versus a text message reminder intervention.

278
00:17:19.737 --> 00:17:21.356
This was a negative trial.

279
00:17:22.257 --> 00:17:25.497
And then Ilana Graetz in the Emory network has

280
00:17:25.757 --> 00:17:29.116
similarly conducted an RCT looking at a symptom

281
00:17:29.156 --> 00:17:32.796
management intervention, a single mode of intervention,

282
00:17:33.256 --> 00:17:37.076
again, in unselected users, and did not find an

283
00:17:37.096 --> 00:17:39.006
effect of that intervention on adherence.

284
00:17:39.096 --> 00:17:42.796
Although there was a signal for possible greater efficacy among the

285
00:17:42.836 --> 00:17:44.616
younger participants in that study.

286
00:17:45.976 --> 00:17:49.936
So there are two second-generation trials in the field currently, the

287
00:17:49.976 --> 00:17:53.656
SWOG 2010 or ASPEN trial, and my group's

288
00:17:53.696 --> 00:17:57.296
GETSET trial in the Alliance for Clinical Trials in Oncology.

289
00:17:57.326 --> 00:18:00.136
And both of these studies focus on more selected

290
00:18:00.236 --> 00:18:03.996
populations. In ASPEN, these are younger

291
00:18:04.056 --> 00:18:07.896
women getting endocrine therapy that includes ovarian suppression,

292
00:18:07.936 --> 00:18:10.906
which steeply increases the side effect burden.

293
00:18:10.936 --> 00:18:14.796
And in GETSET, we oversample women under 50 and Black women

294
00:18:14.856 --> 00:18:18.696
at 30% each. And both of these are also somewhat

295
00:18:18.736 --> 00:18:22.116
more complex and high-intensity interventions

296
00:18:22.876 --> 00:18:26.204
compared to the original trials.And both of these trials

297
00:18:26.944 --> 00:18:29.284
are still in data collection phases.

298
00:18:31.564 --> 00:18:35.204
So our GetSET study was based on a single-arm pilot of

299
00:18:35.484 --> 00:18:36.644
42 women,

300
00:18:37.624 --> 00:18:41.544
over-sampling Black participants in this pilot as well, and is based

301
00:18:41.704 --> 00:18:45.404
on telephone-delivered motivational interviewing using the window of

302
00:18:45.464 --> 00:18:49.404
opportunity of endocrine therapy initiation or the months immediately following

303
00:18:49.464 --> 00:18:53.384
initiation, since we have seen a lot of early drop-off, particularly among

304
00:18:53.444 --> 00:18:56.264
young women, in the first year of therapy.

305
00:18:57.884 --> 00:19:01.344
And in our original pilot, we did see that

306
00:19:01.404 --> 00:19:04.944
the intervention was generally acceptable and

307
00:19:05.284 --> 00:19:09.144
feasible, and that we had high adherence in our cohort overall, which did

308
00:19:09.184 --> 00:19:12.973
not differ by race, although, as I said, we didn't have a comparator arm in

309
00:19:13.024 --> 00:19:16.924
this pilot study. And based on that and

310
00:19:17.004 --> 00:19:20.464
on some work from colleagues at The Ohio State University, Electra

311
00:19:20.584 --> 00:19:23.694
Paskett, Michelle Naughton, and others, who had

312
00:19:23.724 --> 00:19:27.704
simultaneously been testing a text message intervention, we put

313
00:19:27.714 --> 00:19:31.684
these interventions together and designed the GetSET randomized controlled

314
00:19:31.744 --> 00:19:35.504
trial. It features four arms, one with text message

315
00:19:35.544 --> 00:19:39.484
reminders alone. The Hirshman trial data were not available at the time we

316
00:19:39.504 --> 00:19:43.004
designed this study. One with motivational interviewing and counseling

317
00:19:43.044 --> 00:19:43.504
alone,

318
00:19:44.364 --> 00:19:47.984
one with the combination, and an enhanced usual care arm that receives

319
00:19:48.024 --> 00:19:49.664
static educational materials.

320
00:19:51.764 --> 00:19:53.864
This study has closed to accrual recently.

321
00:19:54.304 --> 00:19:57.984
We accrued 1,165 participants, and we

322
00:19:58.044 --> 00:20:01.754
collected primary endpoint data through electronic pill cap monitoring,

323
00:20:02.284 --> 00:20:05.544
and then a large variety of electronic PRO

324
00:20:05.604 --> 00:20:08.964
data at three-month intervals in the cohort as well.

325
00:20:09.024 --> 00:20:12.744
This was designed deliberately to be a very pragmatic, very

326
00:20:12.824 --> 00:20:16.404
outside the clinic study with a diverse sample.

327
00:20:18.264 --> 00:20:21.604
And although we do not have efficacy data from this trial yet, we have recently

328
00:20:21.624 --> 00:20:25.404
been looking at our patient engagement data, and I was happy to see that among

329
00:20:25.444 --> 00:20:29.084
530 women who were randomized to arms that involved

330
00:20:29.124 --> 00:20:30.304
motivational interviewing,

331
00:20:31.424 --> 00:20:35.213
92% of those randomized participants participated in at

332
00:20:35.244 --> 00:20:38.924
least one session, and 81% actually participated in all

333
00:20:38.984 --> 00:20:42.784
five of the MI sessions that we offered them across the

334
00:20:42.824 --> 00:20:46.284
six-month intervention period. So we were happy to see that level of

335
00:20:46.344 --> 00:20:46.904
engagement.

336
00:20:50.524 --> 00:20:54.504
So to summarize some key takeaways, hopefully I've convinced you that

337
00:20:54.524 --> 00:20:58.484
long-term use of endocrine therapy is both common and a really

338
00:20:58.584 --> 00:21:02.464
multifaceted challenge for a large proportion of our breast

339
00:21:02.504 --> 00:21:06.204
cancer survivors, and that it does matter for their disease

340
00:21:06.284 --> 00:21:06.944
outcomes.

341
00:21:07.784 --> 00:21:11.764
When it comes to medication taking in this setting and in any setting

342
00:21:11.824 --> 00:21:15.734
of long-term oral therapy, one size is not going to fit all when it

343
00:21:15.764 --> 00:21:19.284
comes to interventions. We need to think about how to find the folks who benefit

344
00:21:19.404 --> 00:21:23.373
most from intervention. And the early trials are telling us something that really

345
00:21:23.424 --> 00:21:26.844
the HIV world already knew, which is that low intervention,

346
00:21:27.224 --> 00:21:30.993
low intensity, and low touch interventions, single mode interventions,

347
00:21:31.044 --> 00:21:33.184
are unlikely to be effective in this space.

348
00:21:34.484 --> 00:21:38.384
But some promising strategies, in my opinion, include risk stratification

349
00:21:38.784 --> 00:21:42.264
of potential participants in interventions, designing

350
00:21:42.304 --> 00:21:46.264
multi-component interventions with more than one evidence-based tool,

351
00:21:46.684 --> 00:21:49.584
and also being able to reach patients outside the clinic.

352
00:21:49.704 --> 00:21:53.684
I think those of us who are providers are very aware that we have more

353
00:21:53.744 --> 00:21:55.394
unfunded mandates than we can deal with,

354
00:21:56.304 --> 00:21:57.404
and that time in the clinic,

355
00:21:59.304 --> 00:21:59.664
a lot of

356
00:22:01.124 --> 00:22:04.243
subjects and topics and patient needs are competing for that space.

357
00:22:04.644 --> 00:22:08.244
So as much as we can get out of the clinic to reach patients, I think that's going

358
00:22:08.424 --> 00:22:10.664
to help the folks we want to help.

359
00:22:11.484 --> 00:22:15.024
And the new challenges on the adherence horizon, both for breast

360
00:22:15.064 --> 00:22:18.244
cancer and in other cancer settings, are most certainly

361
00:22:18.264 --> 00:22:19.234
intensified,

362
00:22:20.044 --> 00:22:23.044
longer duration, and complex multi-component

363
00:22:23.104 --> 00:22:26.964
regimens. And rising cost is going to be another

364
00:22:27.024 --> 00:22:30.904
challenge associated with access-driven, non-adherence that we're all going to

365
00:22:30.944 --> 00:22:34.104
be facing in the clinic in the years to come.

366
00:22:34.144 --> 00:22:35.404
Thanks so much for your attention.

367
00:22:35.904 --> 00:22:39.894
I couldn't do this without all of my collaborators, both within my

368
00:22:39.964 --> 00:22:43.944
lab and across the country, and I will take questions

369
00:22:44.364 --> 00:22:48.064
at the time of the question session at the end,

370
00:22:48.824 --> 00:22:49.804
when all of us have spoken.

371
00:22:50.904 --> 00:22:54.344
Well, thank you so much. That was a fantastic talk,

372
00:22:54.944 --> 00:22:58.704
and we will transition straight into colorectal cancer. Dr.

373
00:22:58.864 --> 00:22:59.344
Meyris.

374
00:23:06.484 --> 00:23:10.064
So thank you very much. I'd like to first start by thanking the AACR and the

375
00:23:10.164 --> 00:23:13.794
organizing committee for the opportunity to talk on a very

376
00:23:13.984 --> 00:23:15.964
patient-centric question

377
00:23:17.124 --> 00:23:21.024
surrounding the adherence to oral therapies in

378
00:23:21.064 --> 00:23:23.894
colorectal cancer patients. And I'll be talking about

379
00:23:23.894 --> 00:23:27.764
how we're incorporating some of the technologies that we're hearing

380
00:23:27.844 --> 00:23:31.734
about at this conference over the weekend to do better for our patients with this

381
00:23:31.764 --> 00:23:32.284
disease.

382
00:23:33.784 --> 00:23:35.024
These are my disclosures.

383
00:23:36.754 --> 00:23:40.124
So I was asked to answer this question, does adherence to oral

384
00:23:41.384 --> 00:23:43.674
cancer therapies in colorectal cancer matter?

385
00:23:44.184 --> 00:23:47.704
And I think at first glance, the obvious answer is yes.

386
00:23:48.284 --> 00:23:52.044
But as we think about what these drugs are in colorectal cancer

387
00:23:52.264 --> 00:23:56.224
and how this affects the day-to-day lives of our patients and their families

388
00:23:56.284 --> 00:24:00.184
who are living with this diagnosis through the journey, the question

389
00:24:00.224 --> 00:24:02.044
becomes a little bit more complicated.

390
00:24:02.564 --> 00:24:06.144
So to answer this question in more detail, I'm going to divide

391
00:24:06.424 --> 00:24:10.064
the time, the next 20 minutes, into three major

392
00:24:10.464 --> 00:24:14.124
clinical approaches we're taking at our institution to better

393
00:24:14.184 --> 00:24:17.864
address adherence to oral therapies in the day-to-day management of colorectal

394
00:24:17.924 --> 00:24:21.564
cancer. We'll talk about incorporating patient

395
00:24:21.704 --> 00:24:25.074
feedback to minimize toxicity of

396
00:24:25.124 --> 00:24:28.952
FDA-approved therapiesHow we're using circulating tumor DNA

397
00:24:29.452 --> 00:24:33.392
to ensure best practices with oral therapies in colorectal cancer, and

398
00:24:33.472 --> 00:24:37.172
finally, kind of some novel clinical trial approach to make sure that we're

399
00:24:37.292 --> 00:24:40.852
offering best therapies to all patients

400
00:24:42.152 --> 00:24:45.482
with oral therapies in colorectal cancer that are under investigation.

401
00:24:46.712 --> 00:24:50.572
So I come from Houston, at MD Anderson, and as the saying goes,

402
00:24:50.822 --> 00:24:54.772
"Houston, we have a problem." In 2026, colorectal cancer

403
00:24:54.812 --> 00:24:58.512
is the second leading cause of death in the United

404
00:24:58.652 --> 00:25:02.592
States. But under the age of 50, as you can see in the figure

405
00:25:02.632 --> 00:25:06.512
on the left here, it's now the leading cause of cancer-related death under

406
00:25:06.552 --> 00:25:09.822
the age of 50. For men and women and

407
00:25:10.092 --> 00:25:13.212
alike in this demographic, it's the lung cancer

408
00:25:13.312 --> 00:25:17.292
diagnosis for which cancer-related mortality is continuing to

409
00:25:17.352 --> 00:25:19.252
increase year after year.

410
00:25:20.912 --> 00:25:24.752
Because of these alarming trends, new effective therapies

411
00:25:24.852 --> 00:25:28.452
are urgently needed for our patients with this diagnosis.

412
00:25:30.012 --> 00:25:33.932
When we look at what's been approved over the past 20 years

413
00:25:33.952 --> 00:25:37.712
for patients with colorectal cancer, you can see that

414
00:25:37.992 --> 00:25:38.292
over the

415
00:25:39.092 --> 00:25:43.032
past two decades, and especially within the past 10 years,

416
00:25:43.572 --> 00:25:47.232
the majority of therapies which have received FDA

417
00:25:47.252 --> 00:25:50.032
approvals are oral therapies.

418
00:25:50.912 --> 00:25:54.192
So we have to figure out ways to help our patients

419
00:25:55.152 --> 00:25:58.872
adhere to these medications in a way to improve their

420
00:25:58.932 --> 00:25:59.512
outcomes.

421
00:26:01.092 --> 00:26:04.492
One of the questions in preparing for this talk is, what

422
00:26:04.572 --> 00:26:08.072
exactly does adherence mean? And is there a difference

423
00:26:08.092 --> 00:26:10.562
between adherence and compliance?

424
00:26:11.492 --> 00:26:12.542
So compliance,

425
00:26:13.372 --> 00:26:17.092
in some of the research I was doing, was defined as a passive behavior.

426
00:26:17.702 --> 00:26:20.892
Whatever the doctor says is what I'm going to do as a patient.

427
00:26:20.972 --> 00:26:24.712
I just go by their orders. Adherence, though, is very

428
00:26:24.752 --> 00:26:28.132
different. And I like to think of this as a

429
00:26:28.172 --> 00:26:32.112
continuum where an oncologist is providing

430
00:26:32.122 --> 00:26:34.892
the best, most informed practice

431
00:26:36.412 --> 00:26:38.552
tailored to the patient at their point of need.

432
00:26:39.192 --> 00:26:42.942
The patient listens to that information and accepts, "Does this

433
00:26:43.292 --> 00:26:47.241
align with my personal goals of care on this journey?" And then makes the active

434
00:26:47.292 --> 00:26:51.172
decision of how to execute those recommendations in the

435
00:26:51.232 --> 00:26:52.712
management of colorectal cancer.

436
00:26:54.312 --> 00:26:58.252
So with that said, let's talk about first how we've incorporated

437
00:26:58.372 --> 00:27:01.882
patient feedback to reduce toxicity in the management,

438
00:27:01.992 --> 00:27:05.152
specifically of metastatic colorectal cancer.

439
00:27:06.972 --> 00:27:10.612
So I asked my team at MD Anderson, I asked my PA,

440
00:27:10.932 --> 00:27:14.852
my team of pharmacists, our nurses, and I also asked

441
00:27:14.892 --> 00:27:17.632
our patients in a colorectal specific

442
00:27:17.732 --> 00:27:21.632
fashion, "What do you think affects adherence

443
00:27:22.312 --> 00:27:26.132
to oral medications?" And a lot of answers came up,

444
00:27:26.772 --> 00:27:30.332
especially from the patients that we've been asking this question in recent months.

445
00:27:31.892 --> 00:27:33.572
There was a lot of this centered around

446
00:27:35.032 --> 00:27:37.412
first of all, going back to the spectrum I talked about,

447
00:27:38.312 --> 00:27:39.592
optimizing benefit,

448
00:27:40.672 --> 00:27:44.592
recommending the best practices for our patients that are informed

449
00:27:44.732 --> 00:27:48.352
by the newest and most up-to-date data.

450
00:27:49.272 --> 00:27:53.032
When we're giving and offering our best as doctors to our patients,

451
00:27:53.452 --> 00:27:56.452
this engenders trust in our patients to

452
00:27:57.252 --> 00:28:00.932
trust the recommendations that we're recommending them.

453
00:28:02.012 --> 00:28:05.932
And should the patient decide, then the question becomes,

454
00:28:06.192 --> 00:28:09.512
what are the toxicities and side effects of these

455
00:28:09.572 --> 00:28:13.272
medications? How does this affect my quality of life?

456
00:28:13.772 --> 00:28:17.412
And based on where I am in this journey, does this align with my

457
00:28:17.512 --> 00:28:18.292
goals of care?

458
00:28:19.392 --> 00:28:22.992
The reason that I keep harping on this point is when we look at drugs which have

459
00:28:23.032 --> 00:28:26.912
been approved in the past 10 years, specifically oral therapies for

460
00:28:26.952 --> 00:28:27.912
colorectal cancer,

461
00:28:28.792 --> 00:28:32.372
you can see that the difference or improvement in overall

462
00:28:32.412 --> 00:28:35.942
survival for these FDA-approved drugs is on the

463
00:28:36.092 --> 00:28:38.872
order of one and a half to three and a half months.

464
00:28:39.312 --> 00:28:43.192
So we're barely moving the needle forward, and as I'll talk about in the

465
00:28:43.252 --> 00:28:46.802
coming slides, at the expense of significant toxicity.

466
00:28:47.392 --> 00:28:48.802
It really wasn't until the last

467
00:28:50.152 --> 00:28:54.012
of these, which I'll talk about later in the frontline setting for BRAF-mutated

468
00:28:54.032 --> 00:28:57.812
colorectal cancer, that we've seen a substantial leap in

469
00:28:57.912 --> 00:29:00.232
overall survival with oral therapies.

470
00:29:02.032 --> 00:29:05.092
So as we're thinking about these drugs which have been approved in the past 10

471
00:29:05.132 --> 00:29:05.812
years or so,

472
00:29:07.132 --> 00:29:10.912
that in the later line settings, the first trial that I want to

473
00:29:10.952 --> 00:29:14.512
highlight is the Correct trial. This was a phase three trial looking at the

474
00:29:14.572 --> 00:29:18.052
multi-target tyrosine kinase inhibitor, regorafenib,

475
00:29:18.512 --> 00:29:22.132
in patients with treatment refractory, no other standard

476
00:29:22.142 --> 00:29:24.852
therapy available, metastatic colorectal cancer.

477
00:29:25.332 --> 00:29:28.512
Patients were randomized either to regorafenib at a dose of

478
00:29:29.032 --> 00:29:32.052
160 milligrams daily or to a placebo.

479
00:29:32.512 --> 00:29:36.292
And again, this drug got approved by the FDA with a

480
00:29:36.492 --> 00:29:40.132
1.4 month, a six-week improvement in overall

481
00:29:40.252 --> 00:29:43.212
survival. So it was a step forward.

482
00:29:43.852 --> 00:29:47.352
However, it came at the expense of significant

483
00:29:47.472 --> 00:29:50.702
toxicity. As you can see in the first bullet point here,

484
00:29:51.272 --> 00:29:54.632
patients were more likely than not to experience

485
00:29:54.812 --> 00:29:58.632
at least one grade three treatment-related adverse

486
00:29:58.692 --> 00:30:02.512
event, many of which were very physically

487
00:30:02.592 --> 00:30:06.492
limiting hand foot syndrome, oral mucositis as well,

488
00:30:08.092 --> 00:30:11.932
to such a fashion that taking the drug and the side effects

489
00:30:11.972 --> 00:30:15.872
associated with regorafenib did not improve their

