00:45:27.186 --> 00:45:30.906
doses of mercaptopurine, showing that the relapse-free survival

743
00:45:31.006 --> 00:45:34.826
does indeed suffer amongst those who come in remission and then are

744
00:45:34.866 --> 00:45:38.626
placed on oral mercaptopurine. So disease-free

745
00:45:38.686 --> 00:45:42.355
survival in children with ALL obviously depends on disease

746
00:45:42.446 --> 00:45:45.926
biology, which is determined by the somatic

747
00:45:45.986 --> 00:45:48.446
mutations, the chromosomal abnormalities,

748
00:45:49.506 --> 00:45:52.146
and people present with high white counts,

749
00:45:53.046 --> 00:45:55.786
and their age is between one and 10 years.

750
00:45:55.826 --> 00:45:57.786
Sorry, less than one year and greater than 10 years.

751
00:45:57.855 --> 00:45:59.506
Standard disease is one to 10 years.

752
00:46:00.666 --> 00:46:04.366
And how do you monitor it? You monitor it with measurable

753
00:46:04.406 --> 00:46:08.046
residual disease. So if you go into deep remission with

754
00:46:08.166 --> 00:46:11.706
no measurable residual disease, you're doing well,

755
00:46:11.986 --> 00:46:15.626
and the otherwise is true when you have high

756
00:46:15.766 --> 00:46:16.126
MRD.

757
00:46:17.486 --> 00:46:20.936
The disease-free survival also depends on

758
00:46:21.226 --> 00:46:25.116
systemic exposure to oral 6-MP, as I told you, which

759
00:46:25.126 --> 00:46:28.686
can be measured by leukocyte DNA-TG

760
00:46:28.746 --> 00:46:29.246
levels.

761
00:46:30.566 --> 00:46:33.966
This systemic exposure depends on pharmacokinetics.

762
00:46:34.566 --> 00:46:38.466
It depends on dose intensity, i.e., how much are

763
00:46:38.486 --> 00:46:42.206
the doctors prescribing 6-MP? Are they

764
00:46:42.306 --> 00:46:45.966
giving in to the patient who says, "I want a drug holiday because I'm going for

765
00:46:46.086 --> 00:46:46.406
prom,"

766
00:46:47.266 --> 00:46:51.246
or are they actually maintaining that 6-MP drug intensity as

767
00:46:51.286 --> 00:46:54.166
needed? And then adherence to therapy.

768
00:46:54.906 --> 00:46:57.986
So our goal here was to test the

769
00:46:58.026 --> 00:47:02.006
hypothesis that non-adherence results

770
00:47:02.146 --> 00:47:05.726
in low systemic exposure to oral 6-MP during

771
00:47:05.786 --> 00:47:09.486
maintenance, and that results in an increased risk of relapse.

772
00:47:09.496 --> 00:47:12.966
And we were accounting for all the other measurable

773
00:47:13.006 --> 00:47:14.346
factors on this slide.

774
00:47:15.606 --> 00:47:16.826
So how did we measure it?

775
00:47:17.646 --> 00:47:21.486
So the aims were obviously to measure adherence to oral 6-MP in children

776
00:47:21.526 --> 00:47:25.126
with ALL, look at the impact of adherence on relapse

777
00:47:25.226 --> 00:47:28.486
risk using a prospective longitudinal cohort study.

778
00:47:28.986 --> 00:47:32.586
We took children who were 21 years of age or younger and were

779
00:47:32.646 --> 00:47:35.625
entering into maintenance in first clinical remission.

780
00:47:36.286 --> 00:47:39.486
How did we measure adherence? We measured adherence using an

781
00:47:39.546 --> 00:47:40.326
electronic

782
00:47:41.986 --> 00:47:45.816
track cap. These are special pill bottles where there's a

783
00:47:45.846 --> 00:47:49.766
microprocessor chip in the cap that records the date and time

784
00:47:49.806 --> 00:47:51.366
of opening of the medication bottle.

785
00:47:52.506 --> 00:47:56.376
After six months of dispensing the medication in these bottles, we asked them

786
00:47:56.426 --> 00:48:00.246
to mail the caps to us, and we downloaded the

787
00:48:00.286 --> 00:48:04.226
data, and this is what the data download looks like for people who are

788
00:48:04.286 --> 00:48:08.186
adherent. You can see that each blue dot represents the opening of

789
00:48:08.196 --> 00:48:11.966
a pill bottle. On the y-axis is the time, so they're all clustered

790
00:48:12.266 --> 00:48:15.766
within a certain period of time. And then the date

791
00:48:15.866 --> 00:48:19.226
is shown here, so very few missed doses.

792
00:48:19.266 --> 00:48:21.546
And this is what a non-adherent patient looks like.

793
00:48:21.866 --> 00:48:25.306
So these are just visual impressions, but we also calculate the actual

794
00:48:25.686 --> 00:48:26.646
dates of opening.

795
00:48:27.766 --> 00:48:29.626
We measured adherence in the blood.

796
00:48:30.106 --> 00:48:31.846
We measured monthly

797
00:48:33.226 --> 00:48:37.066
6-MP metabolite levels, DGN and MMP, for six

798
00:48:37.106 --> 00:48:40.526
times, and one-time measurement of pharmacogenetics.

799
00:48:41.806 --> 00:48:45.166
We asked the patients to complete a self-report of adherence

800
00:48:45.886 --> 00:48:49.606
in English and Spanish, number of days that 6-MP was taken,

801
00:48:49.746 --> 00:48:53.555
number of missed doses over the past four weeks, and then barriers and

802
00:48:53.646 --> 00:48:57.306
facilitators to adherence. We asked them to complete a demographic

803
00:48:57.386 --> 00:49:01.055
questionnaire, race and ethnicity of the patients and their parents, parents'

804
00:49:01.126 --> 00:49:04.746
education, household income, and family structure and

805
00:49:04.866 --> 00:49:08.138
size.So the

806
00:49:08.198 --> 00:49:11.678
sites that participated completed a maintenance

807
00:49:11.798 --> 00:49:15.638
worksheet. So they filled out a calendar where they described the

808
00:49:15.718 --> 00:49:19.358
prescribed dose for each day and the dates and

809
00:49:19.418 --> 00:49:23.218
reasons why 6-MP was held for each of the days that it was held.

810
00:49:24.018 --> 00:49:27.658
We asked the sites to complete follow-up forms for 10

811
00:49:27.698 --> 00:49:29.188
years, every six months,

812
00:49:30.018 --> 00:49:33.718
with details on recurrence, deaths, and second cancers.

813
00:49:34.198 --> 00:49:36.898
So the patients participated for six months.

814
00:49:36.978 --> 00:49:40.768
On day one, we obtained the consent or assent and

815
00:49:40.818 --> 00:49:41.778
pharmacogenetics,

816
00:49:42.598 --> 00:49:45.718
six monthly measurements of the 6-TGN levels,

817
00:49:46.218 --> 00:49:48.278
demographic questionnaires on the first month,

818
00:49:49.318 --> 00:49:53.298
and then adherence questionnaires, MEMS monitoring of

819
00:49:53.438 --> 00:49:55.738
6-MP, and then download our data at the end.

820
00:49:56.798 --> 00:50:00.168
So 742 children participated in this study from

821
00:50:00.438 --> 00:50:03.558
94 sites across the United States.

822
00:50:03.998 --> 00:50:07.698
How did we calculate adherence? We took the MEMS data and the maintenance

823
00:50:07.738 --> 00:50:11.638
worksheet data, and the adherence rate was the number of days

824
00:50:11.678 --> 00:50:15.608
with MEMS caps openings, divided by the number of days

825
00:50:15.638 --> 00:50:19.118
that the 6-MP was prescribed. And from the denominator, we

826
00:50:19.198 --> 00:50:22.398
removed the days that the 6-MP was withheld by the

827
00:50:22.738 --> 00:50:23.338
physician.

828
00:50:24.318 --> 00:50:26.018
This is what the cohort looked like.

829
00:50:26.048 --> 00:50:29.978
Seven hundred and forty-two patients, median age at diagnosis, five years, median

830
00:50:30.058 --> 00:50:33.908
age at study, six years, 68% were males, and

831
00:50:34.078 --> 00:50:37.978
43% had high-risk disease. So the first question

832
00:50:38.018 --> 00:50:41.958
we wanted to answer was, do children with acute lymphoblastic leukemia adhere to

833
00:50:42.018 --> 00:50:45.538
prescribed chemotherapy? And this was the answer.

834
00:50:46.178 --> 00:50:49.618
Overall, they start off with adherence of

835
00:50:49.798 --> 00:50:52.978
95%, and it trends down to about

836
00:50:53.158 --> 00:50:55.558
90% by the time they're done with the study.

837
00:50:55.928 --> 00:50:59.498
And this trend is statistically significant.

838
00:51:01.658 --> 00:51:05.508
We found that adolescents were less likely to

839
00:51:05.538 --> 00:51:08.398
adhere compared to those who were less than 12 years of age.

840
00:51:09.118 --> 00:51:12.878
We found that those who came

841
00:51:12.918 --> 00:51:16.598
from houses with low income were less likely to

842
00:51:16.718 --> 00:51:20.438
adhere as compared to those who came from high annual income.

843
00:51:21.818 --> 00:51:25.378
Then the next question we wanted to answer was, does poor adherence to oral

844
00:51:25.438 --> 00:51:27.578
6-MP influence the risk of relapse?

845
00:51:28.198 --> 00:51:32.098
And here, what we did was we created five cut points

846
00:51:32.138 --> 00:51:36.018
for adherence, 100%, 95%, 90%, and

847
00:51:36.058 --> 00:51:40.018
85%, so on and so forth. And adjusting for all

848
00:51:40.058 --> 00:51:41.598
known prognosticators of

849
00:51:42.758 --> 00:51:46.638
relapse, we found that as high of an adherence

850
00:51:46.678 --> 00:51:50.078
as 95% was associated with an increased risk of relapse.

851
00:51:50.158 --> 00:51:52.898
So those who had an adherence rate of less than

852
00:51:53.098 --> 00:51:56.818
95% had a twofold higher risk of

853
00:51:56.878 --> 00:52:00.478
relapse than those who were greater than 95%

854
00:52:00.498 --> 00:52:03.618
adherence. And this was true across all adherence cut points.

855
00:52:04.458 --> 00:52:07.658
Looking at the cumulative incidence of relapse, here are the

856
00:52:07.698 --> 00:52:10.078
non-adherers, here are the adherers.

857
00:52:10.898 --> 00:52:14.878
Forty-four percent of our study participants were non-adherent.

858
00:52:15.838 --> 00:52:17.278
Forty-seven percent

859
00:52:18.418 --> 00:52:21.718
of the relapses could be attributed to

860
00:52:22.038 --> 00:52:23.598
non-adherence to chemotherapy.

861
00:52:25.078 --> 00:52:29.038
With this in mind, we said, "Let's take a look at what's the prevalence in our

862
00:52:29.558 --> 00:52:32.798
socio-demographically distinct groups." And here we

863
00:52:32.858 --> 00:52:36.758
show that even amongst the younger children, 41%

864
00:52:36.798 --> 00:52:40.418
were non-adherers. See almost 60% amongst the older

865
00:52:40.478 --> 00:52:40.818
children.

866
00:52:42.478 --> 00:52:45.698
High income, low income. So the

867
00:52:45.738 --> 00:52:49.338
prevalence of non-adherence was high in our population.

868
00:52:49.918 --> 00:52:51.918
Why were they missing their 6-MP doses?

869
00:52:51.958 --> 00:52:55.738
So here I want to take a break to tell you that children, when they

870
00:52:55.798 --> 00:52:59.638
enter maintenance therapy, they're done with their hospitalizations, their

871
00:52:59.738 --> 00:53:02.058
hair's growing back, they have

872
00:53:03.058 --> 00:53:06.978
starting to feel all the energy that they can integrate back into

873
00:53:07.018 --> 00:53:10.378
school, so they're attending all the normal school-related

874
00:53:10.478 --> 00:53:11.258
activities.

875
00:53:12.238 --> 00:53:15.098
6-MP has no side effects. Zero.

876
00:53:15.858 --> 00:53:18.938
6-MP is very cheap. It's been there for decades.

877
00:53:19.498 --> 00:53:23.467
So none of the things that we have heard from

878
00:53:23.498 --> 00:53:27.438
the adult counterparts in terms of the reasons for why people would

879
00:53:27.478 --> 00:53:30.818
be missing doses are generally applicable to

880
00:53:31.138 --> 00:53:35.078
6-MP adherence in children. And plus, 6-MP needs

881
00:53:35.118 --> 00:53:38.918
to be given for a defined duration, one and a half to two years,

882
00:53:39.398 --> 00:53:43.338
once a day. So reasons for missing 6-MP, these

883
00:53:43.378 --> 00:53:46.598
are self-reported reasons, and here's what we find.

884
00:53:46.688 --> 00:53:50.498
And we looked at it across the age groups, the less than 12 years, 12 to

885
00:53:50.558 --> 00:53:52.018
17, 18 plus.

886
00:53:53.258 --> 00:53:57.218
The overwhelmingly large majority of people said they forgot to take it.

887
00:53:58.098 --> 00:54:01.958
Logistic reasons were there. They realized

888
00:54:02.058 --> 00:54:05.758
on the weekend that their drugs had run out and none of their

889
00:54:05.778 --> 00:54:06.938
pharmacies were open,

890
00:54:07.798 --> 00:54:11.638
or they were staying with their other parent in a divorce

891
00:54:11.698 --> 00:54:14.678
situation, and they didn't take their medications with them.

892
00:54:15.058 --> 00:54:17.958
Active refusals were very, very minimal.

893
00:54:18.838 --> 00:54:22.588
Then we conducted a qualitative study where we looked at facilitators and

894
00:54:22.658 --> 00:54:26.618
barriers to adherence to oral chemotherapy, and we

895
00:54:26.638 --> 00:54:29.938
showed that patients and parents who were interviewed

896
00:54:30.058 --> 00:54:30.698
separately,

897
00:54:31.918 --> 00:54:35.438
that all of them described barriers to

898
00:54:35.478 --> 00:54:39.338
medication taking. And forgetfulness was the most common

899
00:54:39.478 --> 00:54:39.858
theme,

900
00:54:40.818 --> 00:54:44.018
such that adherent teens and their parents

901
00:54:44.098 --> 00:54:47.638
emphasized the importance of parental responsibility as a

902
00:54:47.718 --> 00:54:50.198
strategy for overcoming the forgetfulness.

903
00:54:50.738 --> 00:54:54.598
So the adolescents actually welcomed it, or at least held their noses

904
00:54:55.218 --> 00:54:57.538
and accepted their parental vigilance.

905
00:54:58.378 --> 00:55:02.318
Non-adherent teens had difficulty identifying that dyad

906
00:55:02.638 --> 00:55:06.178
situation where they could have the parents be responsible for this.

907
00:55:07.118 --> 00:55:10.678
So thus far, what we've learned is that 6-MP

908
00:55:10.718 --> 00:55:14.206
non-adherence is prevalent.That it

909
00:55:14.266 --> 00:55:18.046
increases the risk of relapse, and that there are certain

910
00:55:18.166 --> 00:55:21.126
subgroups who are more likely to be non-adherent.

911
00:55:22.626 --> 00:55:26.006
So we said, now there's a critical need for an

912
00:55:26.066 --> 00:55:29.826
adherence-enhancing intervention. The major barrier is forgetfulness.

913
00:55:29.866 --> 00:55:33.106
The major facilitator is parental vigilance.

914
00:55:33.586 --> 00:55:36.586
And so with this, we developed an intervention.

915
00:55:37.646 --> 00:55:41.266
The intervention package included a

916
00:55:41.306 --> 00:55:44.566
multimedia interactive patient education,

917
00:55:45.426 --> 00:55:49.046
