01:14:25.658 --> 01:14:28.618
their medication because they have toxicity and don't feel well.

1233
01:14:29.198 --> 01:14:32.858
But how about the opposite, especially in the adjuvant setting where their

1234
01:14:32.898 --> 01:14:35.298
disease may or may not have been cured by surgery?

1235
01:14:35.718 --> 01:14:38.758
Do you ever hear the reason that, "I feel good.

1236
01:14:39.298 --> 01:14:43.218
I don't know why I'm taking this medication. I feel good, and I don't need it"?

1237
01:14:44.258 --> 01:14:47.558
Well, that's exactly what the kids do, especially the

1238
01:14:47.638 --> 01:14:51.148
adolescents. When they go into absolute denial, they feel like

1239
01:14:51.178 --> 01:14:55.108
they're feeling so good that this becomes a secondary

1240
01:14:55.158 --> 01:14:59.098
part of their treatment, and hence the need to make sure

1241
01:14:59.138 --> 01:15:01.678
that there's a parent involved in their care.

1242
01:15:02.098 --> 01:15:03.238
How about the adults?

1243
01:15:04.138 --> 01:15:08.108
Yes. In adults, I would say that this is partly on the clinical

1244
01:15:08.238 --> 01:15:11.948
team, right? Because we need to let people know that when a

1245
01:15:13.058 --> 01:15:16.198
recurrence becomes symptomatic, it's a really bad time to find out about it,

1246
01:15:16.438 --> 01:15:20.098
right? And I certainly have encountered patients who I

1247
01:15:20.138 --> 01:15:24.088
think had the misapprehension that if they did not

1248
01:15:24.138 --> 01:15:27.718
take therapy initially, they could sort of rescue

1249
01:15:28.758 --> 01:15:32.738
a metastatic recurrence with the drugs and start taking them then, and

1250
01:15:32.778 --> 01:15:34.678
of course, that's very much not true.

1251
01:15:35.278 --> 01:15:39.138
Um, and so I think one of the things to be clear about with

1252
01:15:39.158 --> 01:15:43.038
patients up front, um, I compare it to an

1253
01:15:43.098 --> 01:15:46.738
insurance policy, and we talk about why would you have an insurance policy

1254
01:15:46.758 --> 01:15:48.658
when your house is not burning down,

1255
01:15:49.478 --> 01:15:53.318
right? So I think just using clear analogies in lay language with folks

1256
01:15:53.358 --> 01:15:57.108
helps them get straight on why would I take this drug when I'm not

1257
01:15:57.178 --> 01:16:00.478
sick, when people keep telling me my cancer is cured.

1258
01:16:00.578 --> 01:16:04.158
I think in the solid tumor paradigm, that's a really important

1259
01:16:04.218 --> 01:16:07.938
construct to get across to people is why am I continuing on

1260
01:16:08.018 --> 01:16:11.858
therapy of any kind when my cancer is cured or

1261
01:16:11.918 --> 01:16:13.218
I'm cancer free? That's a

1262
01:16:14.778 --> 01:16:18.598
contradiction that I see a lot of people struggle with, and I'm betting that it's

1263
01:16:18.618 --> 01:16:20.218
probably true in colorectal as well.

1264
01:16:20.998 --> 01:16:24.258
I think exactly. You can kind of answer this on both sides of the spectrum.

1265
01:16:24.298 --> 01:16:27.898
I think with the evolving technologies with circulating tumor DNA, especially in

1266
01:16:27.918 --> 01:16:31.738
the stage two setting for colon cancer, um, we're seeing the

1267
01:16:31.778 --> 01:16:35.138
patients who are CTA negative. There's evidence that supports

1268
01:16:35.158 --> 01:16:37.358
de-escalation of care to observation.

1269
01:16:37.818 --> 01:16:41.578
So in those patients who are feeling well and otherwise have a good

1270
01:16:41.638 --> 01:16:45.478
pathologic diagnosis now further informed by a very favorable

1271
01:16:46.058 --> 01:16:48.098
negative ctDNA results,

1272
01:16:48.978 --> 01:16:50.878
de-escalation is

1273
01:16:51.918 --> 01:16:53.438
something we talk about frequently.

1274
01:16:53.858 --> 01:16:57.538
But I'll say just kind of in our clinical experience with the early onset patients,

1275
01:16:58.238 --> 01:17:02.178
what we hear from our patients is, "I am a 35-year-old with two small

1276
01:17:02.278 --> 01:17:06.118
kids at home and my career. Give me everything and more

1277
01:17:06.258 --> 01:17:09.998
because I do not want this cancer coming back." And we actually have to kind of put

1278
01:17:10.038 --> 01:17:13.938
the brakes on that and say, "We could be very well over treating

1279
01:17:13.978 --> 01:17:17.718
you and hurting you by doing that." Um, so in

1280
01:17:17.818 --> 01:17:20.818
the early onset, it's actually the opposite.

1281
01:17:20.838 --> 01:17:21.618
We're like, "Please,

1282
01:17:22.898 --> 01:17:26.578
I will do whatever I can to escalate to make sure this cancer doesn't come back."

1283
01:17:27.318 --> 01:17:27.678
One of the

1284
01:17:28.878 --> 01:17:32.738
really, I think, groundbreaking studies in the past year across all

1285
01:17:32.798 --> 01:17:36.778
of oncology was at ASCO last year, the, uh, Canadian exercise

1286
01:17:36.898 --> 01:17:40.518
study for patients with stage III disease that said if you just

1287
01:17:40.578 --> 01:17:41.868
increase your

1288
01:17:42.718 --> 01:17:46.537
activity level by 10 Mets a week, um, that

1289
01:17:46.598 --> 01:17:50.398
will significantly improve your likelihood, um, for your

1290
01:17:50.958 --> 01:17:54.658
stage III colorectal cancer not to recur and very much

1291
01:17:54.858 --> 01:17:58.078
gave nice evidence of exercise as being an

1292
01:17:58.158 --> 01:18:00.758
anti-neoplastic therapy that improves.

1293
01:18:00.778 --> 01:18:04.398
So we're trying to use that enthusiasm to channel in a healthy

1294
01:18:04.418 --> 01:18:07.858
route, uh, towards more activity, more exercise in our patients.

1295
01:18:08.778 --> 01:18:09.858
Interesting. Thank you.

1296
01:18:12.778 --> 01:18:13.218
Yeah.

1297
01:18:15.118 --> 01:18:18.898
Well, on that note, we're all going to exercise our way back

1298
01:18:18.978 --> 01:18:19.238
out

1299
01:18:20.798 --> 01:18:23.718
to our next session. Thank you so much.

1300
01:18:25.838 --> 01:18:25.927
Thank you.
